<bill id="DLM2469700" in.amend="false" irdnumbering="no" official="yes" xml:lang="en-NZ" year.imprint="2009" bill.no="93" bill.type="government" stage="1" year="2009">
  <billdetail>
    <title>Electoral (Administration) Amendment Bill</title>
    <billtype>Government Bill</billtype>
    <explnote id="DLM2469701" in.amend="false" irdnumbering="no" official="yes" rule-after="yes" rule-before="yes" bill.no="93" bill.type="government" stage="1" year="2009">
      <heading>Explanatory note</heading>
      <explnote.group>
        <heading>General policy statement</heading>
        <para>
          <text>The Electoral (Administration) Amendment Bill (the <emphasis style="bold">Bill</emphasis>) establishes a new independent Crown entity (a new Electoral Commission), which will be given significant responsibility for electoral administration. The Electoral Act 1993, as amended by this Bill, and the Crown Entities Act 2004 will govern the new Electoral Commission.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>This is the first of 2 Bills implementing electoral administration reform.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>Electoral administration is currently undertaken by the Chief Electoral Officer (within the Ministry of Justice), the Electoral Commission (an independent Crown entity), and the Chief Registrar of Electors (the Chief Executive of New Zealand Post Limited, through the Electoral Enrolment Centre). These arrangements can result in the duplication of functions and the creation of confusion and increased costs and complexity for political parties, candidates, and the general public.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>This Bill will establish a new Electoral Commission to perform the functions of the current Chief Electoral Officer and current Electoral Commission as of 1 October 2010. A second Bill will transfer the Chief Registrar of Electors' responsibility for the electoral roll to the new Electoral Commission on 1 October 2012. A staged restructure of electoral administration is necessary to ensure that electoral activity, and the 2011 general election in particular, is not disrupted during the transition to the new arrangements.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>An amalgamated electoral agency will provide for more integrated, efficient, and consistent oversight and execution of operational electoral matters. It is expected that this will result in improved service to the public, candidates, and political parties.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>Part 1 of the Bill implements the first stage of the restructuring of the electoral agencies by amending the Electoral Act 1993 (the <emphasis style="bold">principal Act</emphasis>).</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>Part 1 amends the principal Act to establish and provide for the board of the Electoral Commission. The board will have 3 members, who will be appointed by the Governor-General on the recommendation of the Minister of Justice following consultation with the leaders of the political parties represented in Parliament. The members will be the chairperson, the Chief Electoral Officer (who will be the chief executive of the Commission), and 1 other member. The term of office for members of the Commission will be for up to 5 years and will be renewable.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>The Bill also provides for the Electoral Commission to—</text>
          <list>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
              <para>
                <text>carry out the functions of the current Chief Electoral Officer and current Electoral Commission, which include: conducting parliamentary general elections, by-elections, and referenda; supervising constituency candidate election expense and donation returns; registering political parties and logos; supervising party donations and expenditure returns; reporting on electoral matters referred by the House or Minister of Justice; allocating broadcasting time and funding to political parties; supervising compliance with the election broadcasting regime; and promoting public awareness of electoral matters:</text>
              </para>
            </item>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
              <para>
                <text>appoint deputies to act as members in the case of absence or incapacity (noting, however, that the appointment of the chairperson and deputy chairperson remains with the Governor-General or as otherwise specified by Schedule 5 of the Crown Entities Act 2004):</text>
              </para>
            </item>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
              <para>
                <text>delegate functions, duties, and powers to electoral officials who are not employees (in addition to those to whom the board may delegate by virtue of section 73(1) of the Crown Entities Act 2004):</text>
              </para>
            </item>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
              <para>
                <text>report on the conduct of each general election to the Minister of Justice within 6 months of the return of the writ after the election. The Minister must table election reports in Parliament.</text>
              </para>
            </item>
          </list>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>The Bill also specifies that Electoral Commissioners, Deputy Electoral Commissioners and Returning Officers are disqualified from being parliamentary candidates or from election as members of Parliament. This is to manage a situation that could significantly undermine public confidence in the electoral system, whereby a person administering an election also takes part in it. Likewise, the consequence of a member of Parliament becoming an Electoral Commissioner, Deputy Electoral Commissioner, or Returning Officer will be the creation of a vacancy in the member’s seat in the House. It is currently an offence for a member to continue to sit after having become a public servant, and the Bill extends that offence to a member who continues to sit after becoming an Electoral Commissioner, Deputy Electoral Commissioner, or Returning Officer.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>Section 28 of the principal Act currently provides that the Chief Electoral Officer is an ex officio member of the Representation Commission, which has responsibility for drawing the electoral boundaries every 5 years. This position will be occupied by the chief executive of the new Electoral Commission, in his or her capacity as Chief Electoral Officer.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>The Bill also makes minor amendments to align the principal Act with operational practice (eg, making the Electoral Commission, rather than individual Returning Officers, responsible for printing ballot papers).</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>Part 2 of the Bill provides for transitional matters and consequential amendments to the principal Act, other Acts, and regulations necessary to implement stage 1.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>This includes—</text>
          <list>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
              <para>
                <text>revoking the appointments of the current Chief Electoral Officer and current members of the Electoral Commission:</text>
              </para>
            </item>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
              <para>
                <text>vesting the assets, records, liabilities, and debts of the Ministry of Justice (in respect of the Chief Electoral Office) and the current Electoral Commission in the new Electoral Commission:</text>
              </para>
            </item>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
              <para>
                <text>providing that any matter, thing, or proceedings commenced by or against the Ministry of Justice (in respect of the Chief Electoral Officer), or by or against the current Electoral Commission, may be completed by or against the new Electoral Commission.</text>
              </para>
            </item>
          </list>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>Part 2 also provides for the transfer of employees from the current Electoral Commission and the Chief Electoral Office (in the Ministry of Justice) to the new Electoral Commission, if they agree, on terms and conditions no less favourable than those currently enjoyed. For those employees who agree to be transferred, their continuity of service will be deemed to be unbroken. No compensation for technical redundancy will be available to those employees who are offered equivalent employment in the Electoral Commission, or who accept other employment with the Electoral Commission.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>The Bill includes 4 schedules containing other amendments and consequential amendments to the principal Act, other Acts, and regulations, such as the amendment of the title <quote.in quote="1">Chief Electoral Officer</quote.in> to <quote.in quote="1">Electoral Commission</quote.in> or <quote.in quote="1">Electoral Commissioner</quote.in> as appropriate.</text>
        </para>
      </explnote.group>
      <explnote.group>
        <heading>Clause by clause analysis</heading>
        <clause.desc>
          <para>
            <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 1</emphasis> is the Title clause.</text>
          </para>
        </clause.desc>
        <clause.desc>
          <para>
            <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 2</emphasis> is the commencement clause. The Act comes into force on the day after the date on which it receives the Royal assent, except for subpart 2 of Part 1 and subpart 2 of Part 2, which come into force on 1 October 2010.</text>
          </para>
        </clause.desc>
        <clause.desc>
          <para>
            <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 3</emphasis> states that the Act amends the Electoral Act 1993.</text>
          </para>
        </clause.desc>
        <explnote.part id="DLM2469702">
          <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes">1  </label>
          <heading>Amendments to principal Act</heading>
          <explnote.subpart id="DLM2469703">
            <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes">1</label>
            <heading>Amendments coming into force on day after Royal assent</heading>
            <clause.desc>
              <para>
                <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 4</emphasis> inserts 6 new sections into the Electoral Act. The new sections establish a new Electoral Commission, specify its objective and membership, and provide for the appointment of deputy members. This clause comes into force on the day after the date on which the Act receives Royal assent to enable the new Electoral Commission to prepare for receiving its electoral administration functions on 1 October 2010. </text>
              </para>
            </clause.desc>
            <clause.desc>
              <para>
                <text><emphasis style="italic">New section 4B</emphasis> establishes a new Electoral Commission as a Crown entity.</text>
              </para>
            </clause.desc>
            <clause.desc>
              <para>
                <text><emphasis style="italic">New section 4C</emphasis> sets out the objective of the Electoral Commission.</text>
              </para>
            </clause.desc>
            <clause.desc>
              <para>
                <text><emphasis style="italic">New section 4D</emphasis> provides for the appointment of 3 Electoral Commissioners as members of the board of the Electoral Commission.</text>
              </para>
            </clause.desc>
            <clause.desc>
              <para>
                <text><emphasis style="italic">New section 4E</emphasis> provides that the appointment of a Judge as an Electoral Commissioner will not affect the Judge's tenure of his or her judicial office etc.</text>
              </para>
            </clause.desc>
            <clause.desc>
              <para>
                <text><emphasis style="italic">New section 4F</emphasis> provides for the appointment of Deputy Electoral Commissioners.</text>
              </para>
            </clause.desc>
            <clause.desc>
              <para>
                <text><emphasis style="italic">New section 4G</emphasis> applies the provisions of Schedule 1 of the principal Act to proceedings of the new Electoral Commission.</text>
              </para>
            </clause.desc>
          </explnote.subpart>
          <explnote.subpart id="DLM2469704">
            <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes">2</label>
            <heading>Amendments coming into force on 1 October 2010</heading>
            <clause.desc>
              <para>
                <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 5</emphasis> amends the interpretation section of the principal Act. It substitutes new definitions of Electoral Commission, Electoral Commissioner or Commissioner, and electoral official. It also amends the definition of public servant to include electoral officials (other than those appointed as Deputy Electoral Commissioners or Returning Officers) so that the restrictions applying to public servants in respect of candidacy also apply to people employed or engaged by the Electoral Commission.</text>
              </para>
            </clause.desc>
            <clause.desc>
              <para>
                <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 6</emphasis> repeals sections 4 and 4A of the principal Act, which establish the current Electoral Commission as a Crown entity. </text>
              </para>
            </clause.desc>
            <clause.desc>
              <para>
                <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 7</emphasis> repeals sections 5 to 9 of the principal Act (which deal with the functions, powers, independence, and membership of the current Electoral Commission) and substitutes <emphasis style="italic">new sections 5 to 9</emphasis>. </text>
              </para>
            </clause.desc>
            <clause.desc>
              <para>
                <text><emphasis style="italic">New section 5</emphasis> sets out the functions of the new Electoral Commission (being the functions of the current Electoral Commission and the current Chief Electoral Officer).</text>
              </para>
            </clause.desc>
            <clause.desc>
              <para>
                <text><emphasis style="italic">New section 6</emphasis> sets out powers of the new Electoral Commission, but does not limit the Commission's powers as a Crown entity under sections 16 and 17 of the Crown Entities Act 2004.</text>
              </para>
            </clause.desc>
            <clause.desc>
              <para>
                <text><emphasis style="italic">New section 7</emphasis> provides that the Electoral Commission must act independently when performing its functions.</text>
              </para>
            </clause.desc>
            <clause.desc>
              <para>
                <text><emphasis style="italic">New section 8</emphasis> requires the Electoral Commission to report on the administration of a general election to the Minister, in writing, within 6 months after the return of the writ for that election. The Minister must present any report received to the House of Representatives.</text>
              </para>
            </clause.desc>
            <clause.desc>
              <para>
                <text><emphasis style="italic">New section 9</emphasis> enables the Electoral Commission to delegate to non-employees.</text>
              </para>
            </clause.desc>
            <clause.desc>
              <para>
                <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 8</emphasis> repeals sections 11A, 11B, 14, and 18 to 20 of the principal Act, which provide for matters relating to the current Electoral Commission, Chief Electoral Officer, Deputy Chief Electoral Officer, and electoral officials. </text>
              </para>
            </clause.desc>
            <clause.desc>
              <para>
                <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 9</emphasis> repeals section 20C (which provides for delegations by the current Chief Electoral Officer and Returning Officers) and substitutes 4 new sections.</text>
              </para>
            </clause.desc>
            <clause.desc>
              <para>
                <text><emphasis style="italic">New sections 20C to 20CC</emphasis> enable Returning Officers to delegate functions, duties, or powers to electoral officials. Electoral officials may not subdelegate functions, duties, or powers delegated by a Returning Officer.</text>
              </para>
            </clause.desc>
            <clause.desc>
              <para>
                <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 10</emphasis> repeals section 24, which allows the current Chief Electoral Officer to appoint an employee of New Zealand Post Limited as a Returning Officer.</text>
              </para>
            </clause.desc>
            <clause.desc>
              <para>
                <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 11</emphasis> inserts a <emphasis style="italic">new section 47A</emphasis> into the principal Act, which disqualifies Electoral Commissioners, their deputies, and Returning Officers from becoming candidates or being elected as members of Parliament.</text>
              </para>
            </clause.desc>
            <clause.desc>
              <para>
                <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 12</emphasis> amends section 48 of the principal Act. Section 48 currently makes it an offence for a member of Parliament to sit if his or her seat has become vacant due to him or her becoming a public servant. The amendment extends the offence to any member of Parliament who sits after his or her seat has become vacant due to him or her being appointed as an Electoral Commissioner, a Deputy Electoral Commissioner, or a Returning Officer. </text>
              </para>
            </clause.desc>
            <clause.desc>
              <para>
                <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 13</emphasis> amends section 55(1) of the principal Act to provide that the seat of a member of Parliament will become vacant if he or she is appointed as an Electoral Commissioner, a Deputy Electoral Commissioner, or a Returning Officer.</text>
              </para>
            </clause.desc>
            <clause.desc>
              <para>
                <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 14</emphasis> makes the following technical amendments to the principal Act (as indicated in <emphasis style="italic">Schedule 1</emphasis>):</text>
                <list>
                  <item>
                    <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                    <para>
                      <text>section 39 amended so that the Surveyor-General must provide details of a determination relating to the boundaries of an electoral district to the Electoral Commission, the Chief Registrar of Electors, and other persons or agencies involved in electoral administration:</text>
                    </para>
                  </item>
                  <item>
                    <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                    <para>
                      <text>sections 49, 127, and 146E amended so that the requirements in respect of a person who wishes to become a candidate, but whose name has been removed from an electoral roll through no fault of his or her own, apply to all constituency candidates as well as to list candidates (section 49 currently only applies to constituency candidates nominated by registered electors under section 143):</text>
                    </para>
                  </item>
                  <item>
                    <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                    <para>
                      <text>sections 68, 68A, and 71B amended to reflect that the Electoral Commission will be open for the purposes of those sections until 5 pm rather than 4 pm:</text>
                    </para>
                  </item>
                  <item>
                    <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                    <para>
                      <text>section 150 amended so that the Electoral Commission, rather than a Returning Officer, is responsible for printing ballot papers:</text>
                    </para>
                  </item>
                  <item>
                    <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                    <para>
                      <text>sections 205C, 206C, 206J, 206Q, 219, and 224 amended to correct minor drafting errors.</text>
                    </para>
                  </item>
                </list>
              </para>
            </clause.desc>
          </explnote.subpart>
        </explnote.part>
        <explnote.part id="DLM2469705">
